% You are an expert TypeScript React engineer. Build `pdd/frontend/components/InputField.tsx`, a reusable single-line form input with an optional browse action.

Requirements
1. Export `InputFieldProps` and default `InputField` (`React.FC<InputFieldProps>`).
2. `InputFieldProps`:
   - `label`, `name`, `value`, `placeholder`, `description`: `string`
   - `onChange: (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => void`
   - `required?: boolean`
   - `onBrowse?: () => void`
3. Render a wrapper with:
   - label linked to `name` (`htmlFor={name}`), showing `label` and a red `*` only when `required`
   - controlled text input (`type="text"`) using `name`, `id`, `value`, `onChange`, `placeholder`
   - description text below the field
4. Use a `flex gap-2` row for the input area. If `onBrowse` exists, render a browse button (`type="button"`, `title="Browse files"`) that calls `onBrowse` and renders `FolderOpenIcon` with `className="w-4 h-4"`.
5. Preserve the existing dark Tailwind look used by sibling form fields:
   - label uses gray helper text + `capitalize`
   - input uses translucent dark background with white text and blue focus ring
   - browse button uses gray background/text with lighter hover state
   - description uses small muted gray text

